bug.short_desc: Deploying junit plug-in test to remote Windows machine from a Linux machine fails

long_desc.thetext: When deploying a JUnit Plug-in Test to a Windows machine from a Linux machine the test throws an exception and does not complete. See the attached sample plug-in.

The problem is that the platform.xml file is created based on the features/plug-ins for the local Eclipse installation. This is a problem since:
1) The remote and local Eclipse installations must be of the same build since plug-in IDs contain the build date.
2) The remote and local platforms must be the same OS since the platform-dependent SWT and IAC plug-ins are configured for the local machine and not the remote machine.
#1 should be have a readme entry for this release and 4.4.1.
#2 is causing Joel's problem since he is launching from Linux to Windows the SWT plug-ins are not configured correctly so the Eclipse/TPTP UI cannot be loaded:

Clearly, this scenario was not tested. This defect requires new test cases covering remote test execution between Windows/Linux.

The other problem is that when a user creates a remote workbench location, the workspace path is for the local workspace (including path separators) as well as the target environment (os/arch/ws/nl) is for the local target environment.

(In reply to comment #3) > Clearly, this scenario was not tested. This defect requires new test cases > covering remote test execution between Windows/Linux. >
Since when did we claim to support Eclipse plugin JUnit testing with TPTP? I am not aware that we have tested or claim to support JUnit running in any kind of container. An application server would be an even more common desire, and then we could support Cactus and other server side tests.
